If you've set each GUI to a parameter or to an array then you should be able to access the DOM Element via the `domElement` getter / setter. A hook that would help you in your app is to fire something like this:

```
function removeGui(gui, parent) {
  if(!parent) {
    parent = DAT.GUI.autoPlaceContainer;
  }
  parent.removeChild(gui.domElement);
}

function addGui(gui, parent) {
  if(!parent) {
    parent = DAT.GUI.autoPlaceContainer;
  }
  parent.appendChild(gui);
}
```

where the parameters `gui` represents the `DAT.GUI` you want to remove and `parent` is the parent container where if you didn't specify a `domElement` when instantiating `DAT.GUI` then you don't need to pass a parent. That should do the trick — not sure if there's a need to expose this within the library. Lemme know

